<p>
You've made it another 4 levels. And, if you hadn't noticed already, you'll pick
up on the fact that many of your spells are more powerful versions of previous
spells. From this point on, I will just point out new things. At most levels,
you'll get more powerful versions of things you already have. There's no
need to review them again. You should be
starting to amass money and you should always check to see how much money you
would need to buy your next set of spells so you set aside enough to purchase
them. I'll no longer
suggest which spells you should buy either. You're gaining independence! Of course, I will not curb my need to
expound on history!</p>

<h3>Breaking a Habit</h3>

<p>
At low levels, you learned that if you ran from a mob, you might survive an
otherwise hopeless fight. After all, guards were nearby to deliver a severe
beating to any mob that chased you. But that taught you a lesson that you need
to forget. From this point on, when you are grouped you should never run from a
mob that is hitting you. Here's why:</p>

<blockquote>
  <ul>
    <li>
The mob is hitting you because you made it angrier at you than it is at anyone
else in the group. You need to slow down your spell casting. Don't chain cast
spells unless you have no other choice. It's easy to cast like crazy in a fight.
But, you're less able to take damage than is a warrior or other tank. Your
cleric will use more mana to heal you than to heal the warrior. Your group's
efficiency will suffer.</li>
    <li>
Look around. There are no guards that can kill a mob for you. Where will you
run? Most casters that run at this level run around in circles like a ninny. If
you do that, your tanks will not be able to hit the mob. Which means, they can't
make it mad at them again. You're not going to tire out the mob. It will keep
chasing you. Your cleric will use more mana to heal you….same story. Your
group's efficiency will again suffer.</li>
    <li>
So what should you do if you're tanking a mob and don't want to be? Be sure your
group knows the mob is hitting you so that a tank can anger it or an enchanter
can mesmerize or another group member can root. Back away from the mob slowly. It will switch targets or stop attacking
altogether. Backing away from it slowly
ensures that your tanks can get hit in on the mob. It will also ensure that you
don't get backstabbed.</li>
  </ul>
</blockquote>
