<h3>The Bolt</h3>

<p>
This is the first level you gain a bolt-type spell: Flame Bolt. This spell has a
much greater range than your normal DD spells, but it travels like a magic arrow.
You must have line of sight (LOS) for it to hit. It will follow a moving
opponent, but any landscape geometry, players or pets in the way will block it. A bolt will only damage targets you can attack but it will damage a mob that
gets in your way - even though that mob isn't your target! Be careful firing
bolts from an area that guards protect. You know what's going to happen if you
send a bolt at the back of a guard that jumps in front of you to protect you…(remember
that ducking….D by default…will instantly cancel a channeling spell)</p>

<p>
Bolts fly to the center of most mob models. For now, that's not all that
important to know. Most mobs you'll fight are physically small. But later, it
will be good to know. For example, you cannot easily hit a small beetle with a
bolt if players surround it. However, you can easily hit a giant even if it is
surrounded since the giant's center is above the heads of players.</p>

<p>
Bolts can be &quot;curved&quot; around geometry to a limited extent. If you find
your LOS partially blocked, you can face away from the mob to cast the bolt. The
bolt will start by moving away from you but will &quot;hook&quot; around and
orient on the mob. This has the effect of curving the bolt around something or
someone near you.</p>

<p>
You will find that bolts are generally a sure hit when you are at a higher
altitude that your target's center. Standing on a hill and firing bolts at
targets below you is a good strategy. You'll also find that bolts do not travel
uphill well. They have a tendency to collide with the ground short of the
target.</p>

<p>
<i>Historical Note -
Double Bolts: Bolts were bugged for the first 3 years of the game.&nbsp; Originally, if the player was above the mob, 
bolts had a good chance of landing twice per cast.&nbsp; Although Verant stated it was a display bug only, it was 
clearly hitting twice.&nbsp; In any event, it has been fixed.&nbsp; Regardless of rumor -- bolts no longer land twice.</i></p>

