<h3>Healing the Pet</h3>
<p>
You can now cast your first pet heal: Renew Elements. This spell works just like
any other heal in the game, but will only work on your own pet. It heals 33 hit points per cast. It costs
25 mana points to cast. A quick calculation
will tell you that this spell is not very efficient. For 80 mana points you can
summon a new pet at full health. But, the spell has utility. Summoning a new pet is slower and requires malachite. While fighting,
check your pet's health. If it looks like an extra 33 hp is needed, toss your
pet a heal!&nbsp; This spell improves with each level.&nbsp; At level 9 it will
heal for 34, at level 10 for 35 etc.&nbsp; This spell stops improving at level
25 (50 point heal).</p>

<p>If you have been equipping and/or buffing your pet, healing it might be more
efficient than summoning -- since a new pet will need to be reequipped and
buffed.</p>

<p>Note: This spell also attempts to cure any diseases on the pet.&nbsp;
Depending on the type of disease, you may need more than one cast to remove it.</p>

<p><i>Historical Note: On 7/24/02, the healing penalty to non-clerics was
lifted.&nbsp; Heals will no longer suffer a 10% penalty in hit points healed and
will heal for the full amount.</i></p>

<h3>Damage Shields</h3>

<p>
You can now cast a damage shield, just like the one your fire pet casts on
itself. Magician damage shields are fire-based spells that immolate their target
in flame. Anything hitting the immolated person (or pet) takes a certain amount
of damage for each hit. This damage cannot be resisted and always lands for the
same amount. It adds up quickly. This is one of the most efficient spells you
get. Even at level 60, the damage shield is an important part of the mage
repertoire. Do not cast your spell on your fire pet. The fire pet's shield does
more damage than the one you can cast. This spell type has a short duration.</p>

<p>
The issue of efficiency deserves special attention. Many magicians don't use DS
because they believe they are wasting mana. Many tanks believe they'd be better
off with one more buff (the DS takes a &quot;buff slot&quot;) or are afraid it
adds aggro to them. Let's take the last of these issues first:</p>

<p>
Damage shields do not count as damage done by a player. Many magicians tell
tales about how they cast a damage shield, made a mob angry and died as a
result of it. Don't believe them yourself! The damage from a DS does not build aggro (they don't
make the mob hate you more). However, mobs notice any beneficial spell you cast
on someone they're fighting. And, they may take exception to it. You should cast
the DS prior to attacking. That way the mob won't know who cast the spell.</p>

<p>
We can prove that damage from DS does not &quot;count&quot; toward hate in three
ways:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>1) If a mob dies by burning itself to death on a
damage shield, the corpse will poof and you will not get experience. Why? Again,
damage from the shield does not count against you in terms of aggro. So the game
does not know that a player killed the mob (which proves you the damage did not
  count as damage you did), and&nbsp;</p>

  <p> 2) If you cast a DS on a player prior to the fight and that player dies,
  the mob will walk away.&nbsp; It will not come looking for you (which proves
  you were not added to the mob's hate list), and</p>

  <p>3) You will take faction hits
for kills by players on whom you cast a DS during a fight (which proves the mob saw your DS as a spell that benefited the
  player).</p>

</blockquote>
<p>
As to efficiency, consider first how many times your pet or tank in your group
gets hit in an average fight. It's likely in the neighborhood of 20. But, to be
conservative let's call it 10. Now consider your most power spell: Flame Bolt. Both the DS and Bolt have the same mana cost:
40. Yet, your bolt will hit for a
maximum of 47, while in the average fight your DS will do 10 x 5 or 50 points of
damage. Further, the bolt can miss or be completely/partially resisted. Your DS
cannot miss and always lands for full damage. (It will increase to 6 points at
level 9).&nbsp; As you level, DS becomes increasingly efficient -- especially
since it will last more than one fight.</p>

<p>
Finally, magician damage shields have an important benefit -- they add to fire
resist.&nbsp; If you're fighting a mob that casts fire-based spells, you should
use a DS even if you don't expect to be tanking.&nbsp; It will increase your
chance to resist fire-based spells.</p>

<h3>The Bottomless Bag</h3>

<p>
You're weak and cannot carry much … but you like loot. What to do? Wouldn't it
be great if you had a magic bag that made things put into it weightless? Summon
one! Summon two they're small! But be warned: If you should leave the game for
any reason (deliberately or for reasons beyond your control) for more than 30
minutes, the bag and any items inside of it are gone. Forever. And that's a very
long time.</p>

<p><i>
Historical note: When I was a level 35 magician, bags vanished instantly if you
went off line. There was no 30 minute grace period. One day I was carrying
several summoned bags of weapons to sell to vendors and players. I zoned into
Greater Faydark and was awed to see Tunare! Well, everyone told their friends
and soon Greater Faydark had more players than it could hold. The zone crashed. Poof! 80pp worth of items
vanished. I never forgot that. Not long ago, I was
part of a raid that killed Tunare. The pain of losing my items is starting to
fade.</i></p>

<p><i>Historical note: In my newbie days, summoned items in the bank would not
vanish when a player logged out nor would summoned items vanish due to link
death.&nbsp; People abused these two things by putting stacks of food and arrows
in the bank before logging -- or by deliberately going link dead to save
items.&nbsp; To stop these exploits, Verant changed the game so that summoned
items immediately vanished, creating a new set of problems like the previous
note.</i></p>

<h3>Eye of Zomm</h3>

<p>
How Zomm got his name in the history books is a story for another day. It
certainly wasn't for this spell. This spell summons a moveable eyeball and
changes your camera perspective to it. You can control the movement of the eye
for a brief period. The idea is to use the eye to scout areas without taking
much risk. With the changes to pets, the eye is now completely ignored by mobs.</p>

<p>
Since the Eye of Zomm is ignored by mobs, you can no longer pull by sending the
eye into a room and making the creatures in the room angry.&nbsp; However, you
can still use the eye to obtain a target you might not otherwise be able to
target!&nbsp; For example, you can send the eye into a room and target a
specific mob through the eye.&nbsp; When you return to your own viewpoint
(either when the spell expires or you remove the icon) you will have that mob
targeted.&nbsp; Others in your group or nearby can even /assist you to pick up
that target.</p>

<p>
You can summon and control the Eye even if you have a pet (which wasn't always
the case). The eye is an NPC and isn't a pet, so players can attack it. You'll
find people delight in killing your eye.&nbsp; It has very few hit points and
will usually die in a single hit.</p>

<p><i>
Historical Note: Dueling in front of guards is not a good idea. When guards see
players fighting, they usually want to jump in and stop it. The most efficient
way of doing that is to kill you. A player can kill your Eye of Zomm in front of
a guard without offending the guard. But for some reason guards used to take
exception to a pet killing the eye. One time in North Freeport a magician killed
my eye with his pet and felt the wrath of the Paladin guild. This was fixed long
ago. Guards no longer care if pets kill the Eye of Zomm. It's too bad, really. It was a funny bug...if you weren't an Eye-killer, that is.</i></p>

<h3>Invisibility</h3>

<p>
This spell makes you invisible. Maybe. All undead creatures can still see you. Many mobs will still be able to see
you. Your pet will commit suicide (it can't
see you). And, the spell has a random duration. It could drop at any time
leaving you to say, &quot;Pay no attention to the man behind the curtain.&quot;
But, the mobs probably will pay attention. Invisibility will drop instantly if
you begin casting a spell, start attacking or get attacked. You'll learn that
Invisibility is very unreliable. You'll die more than once while depending on
it.</p>

<h3>
Staff of Tracing</h3>

<p>
You can now summon a staff with rather poor stats that acts as a light source. The staff has 2 charges of
Flare. The staff is 2hb...since your pet doesn't yet benefit from 2
weapons, try giving it a Staff of Tracing!&nbsp; It will increase your pet's
damage output.</p>

<h3>New Focus Item</h3>

<p>
You can now summon a mantle that makes single target buff spells (like your fire
shield) last longer.</p>

<h3>New Pet Skill</h3>

<p>
Your pets will now bash their target for additional damage. The pet will do this
automatically while fighting.</p>
